Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Chop the @potatoes{450%grams} lengthways into 1cm slices, then chop into 1cm wide
chips (no need to peel).

Pop the chips onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with
@salt{} and @pepper{}, sprinkle over the @black sesame seeds{5%grams}, then toss
to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, bake on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}.
Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, remove the @slow cooked beef{280%grams} from the packaging. Place in
an #ovenproof dish{} along with the juices and cover loosely with #foil{}.

Roast on the middle shelf for ~{25-30%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Ensure the beef is piping hot throughout.

While everything cooks, trim the @baby gem lettuce{1%unit}, halve lengthways,
then thinly slice.

In a large #bowl{}, mix together the @coleslaw mix{120%grams},
sliced baby gem, @gochujang paste{30%grams}(use less if you'd prefer things
milder) and @mayonnaise{32%grams}. Season with salt and pepper.

Set your slaw aside for later.

Once the beef has finished cooking, remove from the oven, then discard the foil
and any remaining cooking juices.

Use two #forks{} to shred the beef as finely as you can.

Halve the @burger buns{2%units} and pop into the oven to warm through,
~{2-3%minutes}.

Meanwhile, mix the @bulgogi sauce{75%grams} and @soy sauce{15%milliliters} into
the pulled beef. Season with salt and pepper.

When everything's ready, spread some @mayonnaise{3%tbsp} over the bun bases.
Top with some gochujang slaw, then the bulgogi beef. Sandwich shut with the lids.

Serve with the black sesame chips and remaining slaw alongside.

Enjoy!